Introduction to API Testing
What is client and Server?
A client is a computer hardware device or software that accesses a service made available by a server. The server is often (but not always) located on a separate physical computer.

A server is a physical computer dedicated to run services to serve the needs of other computers. Depending on the service that is running, it could be a file server, database server, home media server, print server or web server.

Client/Server Architecture
1>	1 Tier Architecture – It is not connected to the internet, the client computer directly fetching the information from the file server which is directly connected with the client computers. File server is located under same machine.

2>	2 Tier Architecture – we have multiple client computers, but we are accessing the database server here the database server is in different machine. 
Database server is a separate machine.

3>	3 Tier Architecture – We are accessing the information through the web application to get an information. Here we are getting the information from the server. Client computer -> Application server -> Database server.

What is an API?
Application Program Interface (API): is the way of communication between two applications where applications may differ in their platforms or in terms of technology. (it is a way of communication between two layers)

Presentation Layer -> Application Layer -> Database Layer

Front end of the application -> Middle layer (API layer) -> Back end of the application

Middle layer 
•	This is the responsibility of the API layer to fetch data from the backend and display on the frontend
•	This is also the responsibility of the API layer to take data from the frontend and insert to backend.

What is API testing?
API testing is a type of software testing that validates the functionality, reliability, performance, and security of an application programming interface (API).
Instead of interacting with an application through its user interface (UI), API testing involves sending direct requests to the API’s endpoints and verifying that the responses match expected outcomes.

Why is it needed?
API testing is essential because APIs are the foundation of modern, interconnected software applications (such as microservices architecture) and from the core business logic layer. Testing at this layer offers several significant advantages.
•	Early Defect Detections
•	Improved Test Coverage
•	Faster and More Efficient
•	Enhanced Security
•	Ensures Seamless Integration
•	Language and Platform Independence
•	Facilitates Automation

