Rest API HTTP Methods
What is Rest API?
A REST API (Representation State Transfer Application Programming Interface) is an architectural style for designing networked applications that use standard HTTP methods to enable communication and data exchange between different software systems.

How Rest APIs Work
The interaction between a client and a server in a REST API follows a simple request-response cycle over HTTP
1.	Client Sends a Request: The client sends an HTTP request to a specific endpoint (URL) using an HTTP method, including headers for metadata (like authentication tokens) and an optional message body (for data)
2.	Server Sends a Request: The server receives, authenticates and processes the request.
3.	Server Sends a Response: The server sends back a response containing an HTTP status code (e.g., 200 OK, 404 Not found) and a response body (typically formatted in JSON or XML) with the requested data or the result of the operation.

Request Message -> Application Program Interface -> Response Message

Request Message (Http request) -> Get, Post, Put, Patch, Delete
Response Message (Validations Performed) -> Response Status code, Data etc

Common HTTP Methods
Rest APIs use standard HTTP methods to perform common data operations (often referred to as CRUD operations: Create, Read, Update, Delete)
•	GET: Retrieves a resource or a collection of resource (Read)
•	POST: Creates a new resource on the server (Create)
•	PUT: Updates or replaces an Existing resource entirely (Update)
•	PATCH: Applies partial modifications to a resource (Update)
•	DELETE: Remove a specific resource (Delete)


http Vs https
HTTP – Hyper Text Transfer Protocol is an insecure, unencrypted protocol that sends data as plain text, making it vulnerable to interception.
HTTPS – HTTP Secure uses SSL/TLS encryption to protect data integrity and authenticity. Essential for secure browsing, login and payments.

Key Difference between HTTP and HTTPS
•	Security: Http sends data in plain text, making it insecure. Https encrypts data, protecting sensitive information (passwords, credit cards)
•	Protocol & Encryption: Http uses no encryption. HTTP uses SSL/TLS to create an encrypted connection
•	Port Numbers: Http uses port 80. Https uses port 443
•	Browser indicators: Browsers may mark http sites as “Not Secure”. Https sites display a padlock icon in the address bar
•	SEO and Trust: Google ranks Https sites higher. Users trust https sites more
•	Speed: Http is generally faster, while Https may be slightly slower due to the overhead of encryption

